Introduction

There are many studies documenting that the average global temperature has been increasing over the last century. The consequences of this situation are sadly known. Among these, it is worth mentioning the rising ocean level and extreme weather events that are becoming increasingly frequent. In this assignment we analyze the relationship between the increase in global average temperature and other factors. The dataset ClimateChange.csv contains climate data form May 1983 to December 2008.

The variables of this data set are:

  • Year: The observation year
  • Month: The observation month
  • Temp: The difference in degrees Celsius between the average global temperature in the observation month and a reference value
  • CFC.11: The atmospheric concentration of trichlorofluoromethane (CFC-11), expressed in ppbv
  • CFC.12: The atmospheric concentration of dichlorofluoromethane (CFC-12), expressed in ppbv
  • CO2: The atmospheric concentration of carbon dioxide (CO2), expressed in ppmv
  • N2O: The atmospheric concentration of nitrous oxide (N2O), expressed in ppmv
  • CH4: The atmospheric concentration of methane (CH4), expressed in ppmv
  • Aerosols: The mean stratospheric aerosol optical depth at 550 nm
  • TSI: The total solar irradiance (TSI) in \(W/m^2\)
  • MEI: Multivariate El Nio Southern Oscillation index, a measure of the strength of a weather effect in the Pacific Ocean

Creating test set and training set

To obtain a training set and a test set for the analysis, the original dataset is splitted into two subsets. The first partition, that we assume will be the training set, will contain observations up to and including year 2006, while the second partition will consist of observations after 2006.

training_set = subset(climate_change, Year <= 2006)
test_set = subset(climate_change, Year > 2006)

Building the regression model

Here we start to build a linear regression model that predicts Temp using all of the other veriables (except Year and Month) and the training set.

InitFormula = Temp ~ MEI + CO2 + CH4 + N2O + CFC.11 + CFC.12 + TSI + Aerosols 
climate_regression = lm(formula = InitFormula, data = training_set)
options(scipen=4)

  • Current scientific opinion is that N2O and CFC-11 are greenhouse gases. However, you should see that the regression coefficients of both variables are negative. What is the simplest explanation for this contradiction?

The variables in the dataset are strongly correlated so theres a problem of multicollinearity. The heavy correlation causes some variables to be useless to explain and solve the problem.

Improving the regression model

Here we are improving the regression model building a new one using only MEI, TSI, Aerosols, and N2O as independent variables.

FinalFormula = Temp ~ MEI + N2O + TSI + Aerosols 
climate_regression = lm(formula = FinalFormula, data = training_set)
options(scipen=4) 
summary(climate_regression)

Questions & Answers

  • How does the coefficient for N2O in this model compare to the coefficient in the previous one?

The N2O coefficient in this improved model is positive and assumes the value of 0.025320

  • How does the quality of this model compare to the previous one? Consider the \(R^2\) value and the significance of the independent variables when answering this question.

The new model performs worse than the previous one. It is clear considering the values of \(R^2\) and \(Adjusted R^2\) that are both smaller than those of the first model weve built. Furthermore, all the variables in this new model are significant but, considering the decrease of \(R^2\) value, it emerges that some significant varibles are omitted and so the quality of the model decreases consequently.

Out-of-sample validation

Eventually we apply the second model to the test set to check the performance on previously unseen data.

climate_change_prediction = predict(climate_regression, newdata = test_set)
str(climate_change_prediction)
##  Named num [1:24] 0.504 0.475 0.451 0.439 0.451 ...
##  - attr(*, "names")= chr [1:24] "285" "286" "287" "288" ...
  • Evaluate the quality of the prediction.
plot(test_set$Temp, climate_change_prediction, xlim = c(0,1), ylim = c(0,1), xlab = "Actual value", ylab = "Predicted value")
abline(a=0,b=1, col="red")

Thanks to the graph, its easy to observe that all the predicted values are near 0,4 while the real values are in the range 0,2 - 0,7; so we can conclude that the quality of the classification model is poor.

  • What is the \(R^2\) on the testing set?
SSE = sum((test_set$Temp - climate_change_prediction) ^ 2) # residuals
SST = sum((test_set$Temp - mean(training_set$Temp)) ^ 2)

1 - SSE / SST
## [1] 0.4967795

\(R^2 = 0.4967795\)

  • What does this tell you about the model?

The model seems to overfit the training set, as is evident from the very low value of \(R^2\) compared to the previous one.
